SN  - 1521396x, 00318965
PB  - Wiley
DO  - 10.1002/1521-396X(199702)159:2<R5::AID-PSSA99995>3.0.CO;2-1
AB  - Compared to standard electron spin resonance (ESR), EDMR has proven to be a more sensitive method in detecting paramagnetic states in semiconductors. Its application to electronic devices is particularly interesting because performance limitations in electrical transport can be correlated with recombination processes due to defects. EDMR measurements on group-IV semiconductors in particular silicon are well established. Several recent publications have shown that EDMR can also be applied to III-V compound semiconductors such as GaAs and GaN. Here, GaN for light emitting diodes currently receives considerable attention. Despite of the high brightness already achieved, little is known about defects in such devices and their influence on device properties and stability. In contrast to the older EDMR studies on double-hetero and quantum-well GaN diodes, we investigate here a much simpler GaN p-n junction, which could lead to an easier assignment of the resonances observed.
